[
    {
        "content": "<p>This is half a maths question, half a formalisation question. I hope the location is somewhat accurate.</p>",
        "id": 514420674,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745599585
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>leasen mathlib we have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Submodule#doc\">docs#Submodule</a> which represents a submodule of a <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Module#doc\">docs#Module</a> under the action of a <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Ring#doc\">docs#Ring</a>. Recall that a <code>R</code>-module <code>M</code> is an additive commutative monoid with an action <code>‚Ä¢ : R ‚Üí M ‚Üí M</code> respecting:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>one_smul : 1 ‚Ä¢ x = x</code></li>\n<li><code>mul_smul : (a * b) ‚Ä¢ x = a ‚Ä¢ b ‚Ä¢ x</code></li>\n<li><code>smul_zero : a ‚Ä¢ 0 = 0</code></li>\n<li><code>smul_add : a ‚Ä¢ (x + y) = a ‚Ä¢ x + a ‚Ä¢ y</code></li>\n<li><code>zero_smul : 0 ‚Ä¢ x = 0</code></li>\n<li><code>add_smul : (a + b) ‚Ä¢ x = a ‚Ä¢ x + b ‚Ä¢ x</code></li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 514421133,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745599650
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>... and a <code>R</code>-submodule is a set <code>s : Set M</code> respecting:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>zero_mem : 0 ‚àà s</code></li>\n<li><code>add_mem : x ‚àà s ‚Üí y ‚àà s ‚Üí x + y ‚àà s</code></li>\n<li><code>smul_mem : x ‚àà s ‚Üí a ‚Ä¢ x ‚àà s</code></li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 514422817,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745599957
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In mathematics, there are two very similar notions of <em>G-module</em> and <em>G-submodule</em>, which in mathlib are encapsulated by <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DistribMulAction#doc\">docs#DistribMulAction</a> and... well, we don't have G-submodules.</p>",
        "id": 514423033,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600038
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=SubMulAction#doc\">docs#SubMulAction</a> (edit: apparently not)</p>",
        "id": 514423196,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1745600087
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(it's not closed under addition, and please let me finish)</p>",
        "id": 514423273,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600115
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry, I can't tell when you're finished</p>",
        "id": 514423329,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1745600138
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, please don't jump to conclusions. If the answer to my question was a single declaration in mathlib, I would have found it. <span aria-label=\"smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"smile\">:smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 514423449,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600168
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For a monoid <code>G</code>, mathlib defines a <code>G</code>-module <code>M</code> to be an additive commutative monoid with an action <code>‚Ä¢ : G ‚Üí M ‚Üí M</code> respecting:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>one_smul : 1 ‚Ä¢ x = x</code></li>\n<li><code>mul_smul : (a * b) ‚Ä¢ x = a ‚Ä¢ b ‚Ä¢ x</code></li>\n<li><code>smul_zero : a ‚Ä¢ 0 = 0</code></li>\n<li><code>smul_add : a ‚Ä¢ (x + y) = a ‚Ä¢ x + a ‚Ä¢ y</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>ie we have dropped <code>zero_smul</code> and <code>add_smul</code> from <code>Module</code></p>",
        "id": 514423756,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600264
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We do not have G-submodules in mathlib in full generality, but we do have a special case in the form of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ConvexCone#doc\">docs#ConvexCone</a>. There, <code>G</code> is set to be <code>{r : R // 0 &lt; r}</code> where <code>R</code> is a strictly ordered ring.</p>",
        "id": 514424124,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600388
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I need to prove results about cones in the context of Toric, and in particular I would like to use a result akin to <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Submodule.span_eq_iUnion_nat#doc\">docs#Submodule.span_eq_iUnion_nat</a>.</p>",
        "id": 514424419,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600472
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The precise result I want is that the <code>G</code>-span of a set <code>s : Set M</code> can be written as <code>‚ãÉ n ‚â• 1, ‚ãÉ g : G, g ‚Ä¢ n ‚Ä¢ s</code>. Motivation: If <code>s</code> is open, then <code>n ‚Ä¢ s</code> is open too, and so is <code>g ‚Ä¢ n ‚Ä¢ s</code> (assuming <code>G</code> acts by homeos, which is only true if <code>G</code> is a group!), therefore the whole span is open too. This is <code>isOpen_hull</code> in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/24149\">#24149</a>.</p>",
        "id": 514424916,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600638
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That result (the one writing the span as a union, not the one about the span being open) also holds for usual modules, so it got me thinking that actually <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Submodule#doc\">docs#Submodule</a> is basically the correct definition of a <code>G</code>-submodule already.</p>",
        "id": 514425242,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600743
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The only issue is that I need to get rid of <code>zero_mem : 0 ‚àà s</code>. But actually if I make the axioms of <code>Submodule</code> be</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>add_mem : x ‚àà s ‚Üí y ‚àà s ‚Üí x + y ‚àà s</code></li>\n<li><code>smul_mem : x ‚àà s ‚Üí a ‚Ä¢ x ‚àà s</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>then <code>zero_mem</code> will automatically be true by <code>smul_mem</code> if I can set <code>a := 0</code>, ie if my scalars have a zero.</p>",
        "id": 514425571,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600851
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is therefore my<br>\n<strong>First proposal: Weaken <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Submodule#doc\">docs#Submodule</a> to not require <code>R</code> to be a semiring and to drop the <code>zero_mem</code> field</strong></p>",
        "id": 514425785,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745600914
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>However, there is now an issue: A <code>G</code>-submodule might not be a <code>G</code>-module! or at least not in the sense of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DistribMulAction#doc\">docs#DistribMulAction</a>: The field <code>smul_zero : a ‚Ä¢ 0 = 0</code> would require my <code>G</code>-submodule to have a zero, but quite importantly I want the flexibility to not have a zero (eg <code>isOpen_hull</code> wouldn't hold if I were to force a zero in).</p>",
        "id": 514426259,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745601094
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Therefore come two questions:<br>\n<strong>1. Are you happy with <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Submodule#doc\">docs#Submodule</a> also standing for G-submodules by appropriately weakening the semiring assumption in places?</strong><br>\n<strong>2. What is the correct definition of a G-module? Is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DistribMulAction#doc\">docs#DistribMulAction</a> supposed to encapsulate G-modules? If so, can we change it so that a G-submodule becomes a G-module?</strong></p>",
        "id": 514426583,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745601224
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>cc <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"310045\">@Eric Wieser</span>, as you are probably one of the only people to care about <code>DistribMulAction</code></p>",
        "id": 514428870,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745601944
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you want to allow the empty submodule? (Note that <code>zero_mem</code> forces it to be nonempty. One could replaces it by asking for the submodule to be nonempty; for modules over a ring (or a monoid with zero as long as <code>zero_smul</code> holds) this will imply <code>zero_mem</code>.)</p>",
        "id": 514430254,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Stoll",
        "timestamp": 1745602438
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have not yet found a reason to allow nor to disallow the empty submodule. From the Toric side of things, we certainly don't ever care about empty cones, and most (but not all!) of our cones will in fact be <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=PointedCone#doc\">docs#PointedCone</a> rather than <code>ConvexCone</code>.</p>",
        "id": 514430633,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745602565
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110038\">@Kevin Buzzard</span> this is the thing I was talking about in LLL today.</p>",
        "id": 514430857,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1745602663
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh great! <span aria-label=\"heart\" class=\"emoji emoji-2764\" role=\"img\" title=\"heart\">:heart:</span> I didn't know whether you ended up talking or not. Sorry for ditching last minute.</p>",
        "id": 514430974,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745602693
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually... if we disallow the empty G-submodule, then it's not true anymore that G-submodules form a lattice. That's probably quite a sad fact to lose, no?</p>",
        "id": 514431016,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745602708
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh sorry, I get what you mean. If I want to interface with <code>Submodule</code> then I certainly need G-submodules to be nonempty <span aria-label=\"thinking\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f914\" role=\"img\" title=\"thinking\">:thinking:</span></p>",
        "id": 514431245,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745602778
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Submodules aren't allowed to be empty in maths so that's a big problem</p>",
        "id": 514431955,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1745603042
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do we want to have something like <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DistribMulAction#doc\">docs#DistribMulAction</a> but changing <code>[AddMonoid A]</code> to <code>[AddSemigroup A]</code> (or even just <code>[Add A]</code>)?</p>",
        "id": 514432494,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1745603267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That is more or less what my second question is offering</p>",
        "id": 514434677,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745604041
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/G-submodules/near/514431955\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Submodules aren't allowed to be empty in maths so that's a big problem</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>But maths didn't generally allow for <code>‚ä• : Filter Œ±</code> either (nor <code>0‚Åª¬π</code>), so I don't find that in and of itself to be a convincing argument.</p>",
        "id": 514435585,
        "sender_full_name": "Jireh Loreaux",
        "timestamp": 1745604310
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm a little confused what you're asking for here. Can you just write a candidate definition of the thing you actually need, without the consideration of trying to make it fit into modifications of things we already have?</p>",
        "id": 514435967,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1745604447
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I mean, the candidate already exists and it's <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ConvexCone#doc\">docs#ConvexCone</a></p>",
        "id": 514436037,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745604476
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Should we rename <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DistribMulAction#doc\">docs#DistribMulAction</a> to <code>DistribMulActionWithZero</code> and let <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DistribMulAction#doc\">docs#DistribMulAction</a> just extend <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MulAction#doc\">docs#MulAction</a> with <code>smul_add</code>?</p>",
        "id": 514472375,
        "sender_full_name": "Scott Carnahan",
        "timestamp": 1745621036
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"630477\">Scott Carnahan</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/G-submodules/near/514472375\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Should we rename <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DistribMulAction#doc\">docs#DistribMulAction</a> to <code>DistribMulActionWithZero</code> and let <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DistribMulAction#doc\">docs#DistribMulAction</a> just extend <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MulAction#doc\">docs#MulAction</a> with <code>smul_add</code>?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>But <code>MulActionWithZero</code> is a <code>MulAction</code> in which <code>zero_smul</code> and <code>smul_zero</code>, so calling it <code>DistribMulActionWithZero</code> when it doesn't have a <code>zero_smul</code> doesn't feel right to me.</p>",
        "id": 514478514,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1745625349
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see, it's more like <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=SMulZeroClass#doc\">docs#SMulZeroClass</a> than <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=SMulWithZero#doc\">docs#SMulWithZero</a>. Is<code>DistribMulActionZeroClass</code> too long?</p>",
        "id": 514499554,
        "sender_full_name": "Scott Carnahan",
        "timestamp": 1745642533
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>personally i'd call it <code>AddMulAction</code></p>",
        "id": 514526116,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1745663975
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"630477\">Scott Carnahan</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/G-submodules/near/514499554\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I see, it's more like <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=SMulZeroClass#doc\">docs#SMulZeroClass</a> than <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=SMulWithZero#doc\">docs#SMulWithZero</a>. Is<code>DistribMulActionZeroClass</code> too long?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That's a nice idea</p>",
        "id": 514526140,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745663999
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>or actually, nvm. <code>AddMulAction</code> can cause confusion with <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=AddAction#doc\">docs#AddAction</a></p>",
        "id": 514526213,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1745664031
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This feature is not much used in the <em>Elements</em> but Bourbaki has a notion of group with operators, that would just be an action by a type, and stable subgroups. This is used for modules/submodules, but also for normal subgroups which are stable subgroups when the group acts on itself by conjugation.</p>",
        "id": 514585575,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1745709644
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So I would approve that submodule (and morphisms) rely on minimal assumptions on the nature of the action.</p>",
        "id": 514585684,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1745709737
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does Bourbaki allow empty submodules? empty G-submodules?</p>",
        "id": 514615140,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745734727
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Definitely Bourbaki does not allow empty vector spaces but maybe in more generality this is OK?</p>",
        "id": 514619290,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1745738220
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They only talk about stable <em>subgroups</em>. Monoids appear rarely.</p>",
        "id": 514657711,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1745768762
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>IMO a G-submodule (aka a sub-G-module) should have the structure of a G-module and thus cannot be empty.</p>",
        "id": 514662031,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1745771620
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In general a sub-foo should be a foo‚Ä¶</p>",
        "id": 514662045,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1745771635
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm also confused about the lattice issue... we have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Submodule.completeLattice#doc\">docs#Submodule.completeLattice</a></p>",
        "id": 514668459,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1745776566
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>-module <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> is simply a module over the monoid algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\N[G]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">N</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 514668481,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1745776588
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(\"is\" in the mathematical sense, not the mathlib sense)</p>",
        "id": 514668494,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1745776609
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, not in the sense we need them for <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ConvexCone#doc\">docs#ConvexCone</a>. It's very important we do not require a G-module to have a zero, cf the argument in <a class=\"message-link\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/G-submodules/near/514424916\">#maths &gt; G-submodules @ üí¨</a></p>",
        "id": 514668622,
        "sender_full_name": "Ya√´l Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1745776697
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm sorry, but if it doesn't have zero, then IMO you should not call it a submodule.</p>",
        "id": 514668646,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1745776727
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you have a semiring <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> and an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span>-module <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>, then you can talk about <em>convex</em> linear combinations, i.e. linear combinations of the form <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>‚ãØ</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a_1 m_1 + \\cdots + a_n m_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">‚ãØ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5806em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>‚ãØ</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a_1 + \\cdots + a_n = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">‚ãØ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5806em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>. I guess you want convex cone to be some subset which is closed under such combinations (and under scalar multiplication)? the current definition agrees with this notion in some cases, but why would you want to call it a submodule? The algebraic structure is completely different. In principle you can have an algebraic structure on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> where one could talk about such convex combinations, and this would be a module over that kind of algebraic object (in the sense of universal algebra).</p>",
